08006nam a22009015i 9780226606040DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226606040  a(DE-B1597)523329  a(OCoLC)1080313822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aT174.3b.H69 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a303.48/322300aHow Knowledge Moves :bWriting the Transnational History of Science and Technology /ced. by John Krige. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b13 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Writing the Transnational History of Science and Technology -- tPart I. The US Regulatory State -- tChapter 1. Restricting the Transnational Movement of “Knowledgeable Bodies”: The Interplay of US Visa Restrictions and Export Controls in the Cold War -- tChapter 2. Export Controls as Instruments to Regulate Knowledge Acquisition in a Globalizing Economy -- tPart II. Colonial and Postcolonial Contexts -- tChapter 3. California Cloning in French Algeria: Rooting Pieds Noirs and Uprooting Fellahs in the Orange Groves of the Mitidja -- tChapter 4. Modalities of Modernization: American Technic in Colonial and Postcolonial India -- tChapter 5. Transnational Knowledge, American Hegemony: Social Scientists in US-Occupied Japan -- tChapter 6. Dispersed Sites: San Marco and the Launch from Kenya -- tChapter 7. Bringing the Environment Back In: A Transnational History of Landsat -- tPart III. Individual Identities in Flux -- tChapter 8. Manuel Sandoval Vallarta: The Rise and Fall of a Transnational Actor at the Crossroad of World War II Science Mobilization -- tChapter 9. The Officer’s Three Names: The Formal, Familiar, and Bureaucratic in the Transnational History of Scientific Fellowships -- tChapter 10. Scientific Exchanges between the United States and Brazil in the Twentieth Century: Cultural Diplomacy and Transnational Movements -- tChapter 11. The Transnational Physical Science Study Committee: The Evolving Nation in the World of Science and Education (1945–1975) -- tPart IV. The Nuclear Regime -- tChapter 12. Technical Assistance in Movement: Nuclear Knowledge Crosses Latin American Borders -- tChapter 13. Controlled Exchanges: Public-Private Hybridity, Transnational Networking, and Knowledge Circulation in US-China Scientific Discourse on Nuclear Arms Control -- tAfterword: Reflections on Writing the Transnational History of Science and Technology -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKnowledge matters, and states have a stake in managing its movement to protect a variety of local and national interests. The view that knowledge circulates by itself in a flat world, unimpeded by national boundaries, is a myth. The transnational movement of knowledge is a social accomplishment, requiring negotiation, accommodation, and adaptation to the specificities of local contexts. This volume of essays by historians of science and technology breaks the national framework in which histories are often written. Instead, How Knowledge Moves takes knowledge as its central object, with the goal of unraveling the relationships among people, ideas, and things that arise when they cross national borders. This specialized knowledge is located at multiple sites and moves across borders via a dazzling array of channels, embedded in heads and hands, in artifacts, and in texts. In the United States, it shapes policies for visas, export controls, and nuclear weapons proliferation; in Algeria, it enhances the production of oranges by colonial settlers; in Vietnam, it facilitates the exploitation of a river delta. In India it transforms modes of agricultural production. It implants American values in Latin America. By concentrating on the conditions that allow for knowledge movement, these essays explore travel and exchange in face-to-face encounters and show how border-crossings mobilize extensive bureaucratic technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSciencexInternational cooperationvCross-cultural studies. 0aSciencezUnited StatesxInternational cooperationxHistoryy20th century. 0aTechnology transfervCross-cultural studies. 0aTechnology transferzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aUnited States.  aglobal networks.  aknowhow.  aknowledge in movement.  aknowledge/power.  anational borders.  anational interests.  anationality.  aregulatory state.1 aBarany, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreire, Olival, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingsberg Kadia, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrige, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrige, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKumar, Prakash, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaher, Neil M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMateos, Gisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinor, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaraiva, Tiago, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiddiqi, Asif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilva, Indianara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Josep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel